Troubleshooting Scenarios
Scenario 1: Desktop Computer Not Powering On
Problem Description

A desktop computer in the Finance department fails to power on during working hours, preventing the employee from accessing company systems and performing daily tasks.

Symptoms
No power indicator lights
Blank monitor screen
No fan or hard drive noise
Keyboard and mouse lights not turning on
Possible Causes
Faulty power cable
Defective power supply unit (PSU)
Power outage or faulty wall socket
UPS malfunction
Internal hardware failure
Troubleshooting Steps
Verify that the power cable is securely connected to both the computer and the wall socket.
Test the wall socket using another device.
Check whether the UPS is functioning correctly.
Replace the power cable with a working cable.
Open the desktop case and inspect for loose internal connections.
Test the PSU using a PSU tester or replace it temporarily.
Check for motherboard indicator lights.
Resolution

The faulty power cable was replaced, and the desktop powered on successfully.

Scenario 2: No Internet Connectivity
Problem Description

Employees in the Sales and Marketing department are unable to access the internet, preventing them from using cloud applications, email services, and communication tools.

Symptoms
“No Internet Access” notification displayed
Web pages failing to load
Unable to access email or online systems
Network icon showing disconnected status
Wi-Fi connected but no internet available
Possible Causes
Router or modem failure
DNS server issues
Disconnected Ethernet cable
ISP outage
Incorrect IP configuration
Network adapter malfunction
Troubleshooting Steps
Verify whether other devices are connected to the internet.
Restart the router and modem.
Check Ethernet cable connections.
Run network diagnostics on the affected computer.
Use commands such as:
ipconfig
ping 8.8.8.8
ping google.com
Flush DNS cache:
ipconfig /flushdns
Restart the network adapter.
Contact the Internet Service Provider to confirm outages.
Resolution

The issue was caused by a disconnected Ethernet cable between the router and switch. Reconnecting the cable restored internet connectivity.

Scenario 3: Printer Offline
Problem Description

Employees are unable to print documents because the shared office printer appears offline on all connected computers.

Symptoms
Printer status showing “Offline”
Print jobs stuck in queue
Error messages when printing
Printer not responding to print requests
Printer unavailable on the network
Possible Causes
Printer disconnected from the network
Incorrect printer driver installation
IP address conflict
Print spooler service failure
Paper jam or low toner
Printer queue stuck
Troubleshooting Steps
Ensure the printer is powered on.
Check network or USB cable connections.
Restart the printer.
Verify the printer’s IP address configuration.
Restart the Print Spooler service.
Clear the print queue.
Reinstall or update printer drivers.
Print a test page to confirm functionality.
Resolution

The print queue was cleared, and the printer driver was reinstalled. Printing services returned to normal operation. 